## FEATURE 2 — Role-based query context file

### What to build

A new optional CLI argument on the scaffold command:

  dynamoui scaffold --adapter postgresql --schema public \
    --output-dir ./skills/ \
    --seed-patterns \
    --context-file ./business_context.yaml

The context file is a YAML file with this structure:

  roles:
    - name: Store Operator
      entities: [Invoice, Customer]      # optional; omit to apply to all entities
      queries:
        - "last 5 purchases by a customer"
        - "invoices from last month"
        - "total revenue this month"
        - "which customers have spent the most"
    - name: Finance
      entities: [Invoice]
      queries:
        - "monthly invoice summary for last 6 months"
        - "revenue by country"
        - "average order value this quarter"
    - name: Music Buyer
      entities: [Track, Album, Genre]
      queries:
        - "top genres by number of purchases"
        - "best selling albums this year"
        - "tracks never purchased"

The entities list scopes which entities receive that role's queries in
their patterns file and widgets. If entities is omitted, the role's
queries are included for every entity.

### How it feeds the LLM seeder

When --context-file is provided, the PatternSeeder prompt for each entity
is extended with a "Business use cases" section listing the queries from
roles whose entities list includes that entity (or all roles if no scoping).

  Example addition to the seeder prompt for Invoice:

    Business use cases:
    Store Operator asks:
      - "last 5 purchases by a customer"
      - "invoices from last month"
      - "total revenue this month"
      - "which customers have spent the most"
    Finance asks:
      - "monthly invoice summary for last 6 months"
      - "revenue by country"
      - "average order value this quarter"

    Generate patterns that address these use cases directly. Each query
    above should map to at least one pattern with that query (or a close
    paraphrase) as a trigger.

This means the typical_queries become first-class pattern triggers
verbatim — not just hints. The LLM is explicitly instructed to cover them.

### How it feeds widget generation

Widgets generated from seeded patterns use:
  - category: the role name from the context file whose query triggered the pattern
  - title: the original query string from the context file (not the pattern id)

If a pattern was not derived from a context file query (i.e. the LLM
generated it independently), widget category falls back to the entity name
and title is derived from the pattern description.

The result is a widget list grouped by business role rather than by entity,
which is what a business user dashboard should look like.

### domain_roles in skill YAML

After successful seeding, the scaffolder writes the role/query pairs that
were used for that entity back into the skill YAML under domain_roles.
This makes the context file's content part of the versioned skill definition
and means future re-scaffolds or LLM synthesis calls have the role context
available without needing the context file again.

  domain_roles:
    - role: Store Operator
      typical_queries:
        - "last 5 purchases by a customer"
        - "invoices from last month"
    - role: Finance
      typical_queries:
        - "monthly invoice summary for last 6 months"

domain_roles is a new optional field on EntitySkill. Default: empty list.

