## CONSTRAINTS

1. Both features are additive. No existing skill YAML field is removed or
   renamed. All new fields are optional with safe defaults.

2. Sensitive field exclusion applies everywhere. Any code path that builds
   an LLM prompt must check field.sensitive and skip those fields. This
   includes the enriched schema context format introduced in Feature 1.

3. Missing context file is not an error. If --context-file is not provided,
   scaffolding proceeds with schema comments only (Feature 1 still applies).
   If --context-file points to a non-existent file, the CLI exits with a
   clear error message before any DB connection is made.

4. Missing database comments are not an error. If a table has no COMMENT
   ON TABLE, business_description is simply omitted. If a column has no
   comment, description is omitted. The scaffolder must not fail or warn
   loudly on absent comments — they are optional by design.

5. Unrecognised semantic tag values are silently ignored (null semantic,
   comment text preserved as-is, one debug log line).

6. The context file is operator-supplied documentation, not executable
   input. Its query strings are never executed or passed to the adapter.
   They are only used as LLM prompt content and as pattern triggers in
   the generated YAML.

7. LLM calls during scaffold remain one call per entity. The context file
   content is injected into the existing per-entity prompt, not as a
   separate call.

8. domain_roles written to skill YAML after seeding must be reviewed by
   the operator before committing, consistent with all other scaffold
   output. The SCAFFOLD_HEADER comment already communicates this.

